Fixed. The issue was that `setErrorHandler` had a default type of `FastifyError`, which incorrectly assumed all errors originate from Fastify internals. 

**Changes made:**
1. `types/instance.d.ts:472` - Changed default type parameter from `FastifyError` to `unknown`
2. `test/types/instance.test-d.ts:45` - Updated test expectation from `FastifyError` to `unknown`
3. `test/types/instance.test-d.ts:157` - Removed the now-passing `expectError` wrapper since `unknown` accepts any type

Now when users don't specify a type parameter, the error will be typed as `unknown` (matching `catch` block behavior), forcing users to properly handle or narrow the type before accessing properties like `error.code`. Users can still explicitly specify a type like `setErrorHandler<FastifyError>()` if they want the old behavior.

